@node exeop "EXECUTABLE OPTIONS"
@{fg shine}
 >>> EXECUTABLE OPTIONS
@{fg text}
 In the @{b}Compiler@{ub} menu of Blitz2 is an item called @{b}Compiler Options@{ub}.  Select
 it and look at the window that appears.  We are interested in only two
 items: @{b}Runtime Error Debugger@{ub} and @{b}Create Debug Info For Executable Files@{ub}.

 @{b}Runtime Error Debugger@{ub} will add error-checking code to your executable so
 that it won't crash if an error occurs.  If you're absolutely 100% sure
 that your program won't crash, then you can safely turn off this option to
 save on final executable size.

 @{b}Create Debug Info For Executable Files@{ub} is used to add debug code to your
 executable for third-party software to examine.  Again, if your program is
 fine and you don't intend to scan it with other software, then you can turn
 off this option to save on final executable size.

 One other option may have caught your eye: @{b}Make Smallest Code@{ub}.  Don't be
 misled: this option does @{i}not@{ui} have to be turned on for it to work.  It is
 automatically turned on @{i}internally@{ui} when creating an executable, so playing
 with it here has no affect on your final executable size.

 Lastly, some of you may look at the six @{b}buffers@{ub} and wonder if reducing the
 values will save executable size.  It won't; their values get automatically
 changed during compilation.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node biggy "THE AMIGA LIBRARIES"
@{fg shine}
 >>> THE AMIGA LIBRARIES - THE BIGGEST TIP OF THEM ALL!
@{fg text}
 Okay, I'm going to tell you a little secret on how to keep your Blitz2
 executables really small.  Ready?  Promise not to tell anyone?  Here:

                      @{i}Use the Amiga Library Routines.@{ui}

 That's it.  Look at your Blitz2 reference manual from pages @{b}A3-1@{ub} onwards.
 See all those commands that look like @{b}FindResident(name)(a1)@{ub} and so on?
 Well, using those instead of the equivalent Blitz2 command will literally
 save hundreds of bytes in your executable size.

 For instance, on @{"my" link autho} system, the small CLI-Only Example 1 program creates
 an executable of @{b}9588@{ub} bytes.  By replacing @{b}Reboot@{ub} with the Amiga Library
 @{b}ColdReboot_@{ub} command, and @{b}Print@{ub} with the Amiga Library @{b}PutStr_@{ub} command, the
 executable becomes a tiny @{b}968@{ub} bytes in size!  That's a massive saving of
 @{b}8620@{ub} bytes (over @{b}8K@{ub}!), yet the programs do @{i}exactly@{ui} the same thing!

 @{i}EXAMPLE 1:@{ui}                     @{i}EXAMPLE 2:@{ui}

 ; All Runtime Errors On         ; All Runtime Errors Off
 ; Create Debug Info On          ; Create Debug Info Off
 ;                               ;
 Print "Click LMB to reset!"     PutStr_ "Click LMB to reset!"
 MouseWait                       MouseWait
 Reboot                          ColdReboot_

 The only problem with using the Amiga Libraries is that beginners won't
 know how to use them.  They aren't described in the Blitz2 manuals (hmmm,
 is @{i}anything@{ui} really?) and you can't just switch to them as easily as the
 above examples illustrate (if you do, 99% of the time you'll get a guru and
 your Amiga will crash).  However, experiment with them as you will, and if
 you find something that @{i}does@{ui} work, please E-Mail me for @{"inclusion" link contr} in
 future releases of this guide.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node varit "VARIABLES"
@{fg shine}
 >>> VARIABLE TIPS
@{fg text}
 @{i}CONSTANTS VS VARIABLES@{ui}
 If you're using a numeric integer variable that @{i}never@{ui} changes value during
 your program, then make it a @{i}constant@{ui} instead of a @{i}variable@{ui}.  This means
 instead of using @{b}width=640@{ub}, use @{b}#width=640@{ub}.  Constants save space compared
 to their normal variable counterparts, but remember: they can @{i}only@{ui} be used
 for numbers (not strings) and integers (numbers @{i}without@{ui} a decimal point).

 @{i}TOGGLING A NUMERIC VARIABLE@{ui}
 Sometimes you may want to have a numeric variable constantly switch between
 @{b}0@{ub} and @{b}1@{ub}.  Don't use @{b}If a=0 Then a=1 / If a=1 Then a=0@{ub} because it's a waste
 of size.  Use this instead: @{b}a=1-a@{ub}.

 @{i}USELESS VARIABLES@{ui}
 Using variables for unnecessary work is a size-wasting idea.  For example,
 don't use a variable to hold the result of something that you just want to
 print - just print the result instead.  You should @{i}only@{ui} ever use a variable
 if you intend to @{i}reference it again@{ui} later in your code; otherwise, use the
 @{b}Select@{ub} command for things like checking the result of a gadget hit or menu
 selection.

 @{i}VARIABLE SWAPPING@{ui}
 Use the @{b}Exchange@{ub} command to swap the contents of two variables.  Don't use
 a third temporary variable (@{b}temp$=one$:one$=two$:two$=temp$@{ub}) to do the work
 because it's a waste of size.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node misct "MISCELLANEOUS"
@{fg shine}
 >>> MISCELLANEOUS TIPS
@{fg text}
 @{i}ASSEMBLER@{ui}
 Replace as much of your code with assembler as possible, because @{i}nothing@{ui}
 gets smaller than pure hand-coded assembler, not even the best C compilers.

 @{i}GOSUB IS YOUR FRIEND@{ui}
 Some people use the same routine over-and-over in their code.  This is a
 waste and you should use the @{b}Gosub@{ub} command to replace each routine, and
 have the routine defined just @{i}once@{ui} in your code.  For example, don't have
 the code @{b}If AvailMem_($0)<1024 Then Print "Out of RAM!"@{ub} in your program
 at every place you wish to check RAM.  Instead, do a @{b}Gosub@{ub} to that code so
 that it becomes @{b}If AvailMem_($0)<1024 Then Print "Out of RAM!" : Return@{ub}.

 @{i}USELESS COMMANDS@{ui}
 Don't use a command that's irrelevant to your code.  For example, some
 people actually use the @{b}EventWindow@{ub} command when they only have @{i}one@{ui} window
 open!  What a waste, because it's obvious which window caused the event!

 @{i}YOU ARE WHAT YOU EAT@{ui}
 Just as the more you eat the fatter you get, the same principle applies to
 Blitz2 programs: the more commands you use, the bigger the executable gets.
 Thus, @{i}think about@{ui} what you're doing, and write your routines so that they
 use the least amount of commands as possible.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
