@node tipa "'A' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "A"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 ACTIVATE (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you're opening a window and instantly activating it with @{b}Activate@{ub}, then
 you're wasting bytes.  Instead, just add the value @{b}$1000@{ub} to the window's
 flags.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Window #,X,Y,Width,Height,$Flags,Title,DPen,BPen : Activate #
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} Window #,X,Y,Width,Height,$Flags|$1000,Title,DPen,BPen
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipb "'B' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
 >>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "B"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 BEEPSCREEN (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you're using @{b}BeepScreen@{ub} with screen @{b}0@{ub} then use @{b}DisplayBeep_@{ub} instead.
 Note that this tip @{i}only@{ui} works for screen 0 and no others.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} BeepScreen 0
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} DisplayBeep_0
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipc "'C' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
 >>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "C"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 CHANGEDIR (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}
@{fg text}
 Use @{b}CHDir@{ub} instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} ChangeDir dir$
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} CHDir dir$
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 CHIPFREE (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use @{b}AvailMem_@{ub} instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} chip=ChipFree
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} chip=AvailMem_($20002)
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipe "'E' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "E"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 EXEC (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use @{b}Execute_@{ub} instead.  If you don't include the @{b}run >nil:@{ub} part, then your
 program will halt until the DOS command ends.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Exec dos$
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} Execute_ "run >nil: "+dos$,0,0
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipf "'F' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
 >>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "F"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 FASTFREE (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use @{b}AvailMem_@{ub} instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} fast=FastFree
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} fast=AvailMem_($20004)
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 FILTER OFF (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use assembler instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Filter Off
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} MOVE #253,$bfe001
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 FILTER ON (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use assembler instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Filter On
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} MOVE #2,$bfe001
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 FLOATMODE (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you're using the @{b}Format@{ub} command, then you don't need to use @{b}FloatMode@{ub}
 because @{b}Format@{ub} automatically invokes a floatmode of -1.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Format "000000000" : FloatMode -1 : NPrint 9^9
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} Format "000000000" : NPrint 9^9
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 FORCENTSC (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use assembler instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} ForceNTSC
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} MOVE #0,$dff1dc
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 FORCEPAL (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use assembler instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} ForcePAL
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} MOVE #32,$dff1dc
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipi "'I' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "I"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 IF [Tip 1] (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you're testing a numeric variable for the value @{b}1@{ub}, then don't use @{b}=1@{ub} as
 part of the test.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} If a=1 Then NPrint "1"
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} If a Then NPrint "1"
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 IF [Tip 2] (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you're testing @{i}two@{ui} variables and the result will be a small block of
 code with no @{b}Goto@{ub}s or @{b}Gosub@{ub}s or further test conditions, then use @{b}Else@{ub}
 instead of two @{b}If@{ub}s.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} If a=1 Then NPrint "1"
      If a=2 Then NPrint "2"

 @{i}NEW:@{ui} If a=1 Then NPrint "1" Else NPrint "2"
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 IF [Tip 3] (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you're testing @{i}two@{ui} variables and the result will be a large block of
 code, or has @{b}Gotos@{ub} or @{b}Gosubs@{ub} or further test conditions, then use @{b}Else@{ub}
 and @{b}EndIf@{ub} instead of multiple @{b}If@{ub}s.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} If a=1 Then NPrint "1" : If b=1 Then Goto loop1
      If a=2 Then NPrint "2" : If b=2 Then Goto loop2

 @{i}NEW:@{ui} If a=1
        NPrint "1" : If b=1 Then Goto loop1
      Else
        NPrint "2" : If b=2 Then Goto loop2
      EndIf
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 IF [Tip 4] (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you're testing @{i}more@{ui} than two variables, use @{b}Select@{ub} and @{b}Case@{ub} instead of
 multiple @{b}If@{ub}s.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} If a=1 Then NPrint "1" : Goto loop1
      If a=2 Then NPrint "2" : Goto loop2
      If a=3 Then NPrint "3" : Goto loop3

 @{i}NEW:@{ui} Select a
        Case 1
          NPrint "1" : Goto loop1
        Case 2
          NPrint "2" : Goto loop2
        Case 3
          NPrint "3" : Goto loop3
      End Select
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipk "'K' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "K"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 KEYCODE (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use @{b}Peek@{ub} instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} key=KeyCode
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} key=Peek($bfec00) AND $ff
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 KILLFILE (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use @{b}DeleteFile_@{ub} instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} KillFile filename$
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} DeleteFile_ filename$
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipl "'L' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "L"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 LOADPALETTE (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 The @{b}LoadScreen@{ub} command can optionally load the associated palette with it,
 so don't use @{b}LoadScreen@{ub} and @{b}LoadPalette@{ub} for the same screen.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} LoadScreen screen#,filename$ : LoadPalette screen#,filename$
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} LoadScreen screen#,filename$,palette#
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipm "'M' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "M"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 MEMFREE (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use @{b}AvailMem_@{ub} instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} free=MemFree
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} free=AvailMem_($0)
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 MENUSOFF (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you don't intend to use menus with a window, then @{i}don't@{ui} use @{b}MenusOff@{ub} to
 specify this.  Instead, add the value @{b}$10000@{ub} to the window's flags.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Window #,X,Y,Width,Height,$Flags,Title,DPen,BPen : MenusOff
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} Window #,X,Y,Width,Height,$Flags|$10000,Title,DPen,BPen
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipn "'N' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "N"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 NAMEFILE (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you're using @{i}variables@{ui} to specify the old/new names, then use @{b}Rename_@{ub}
 instead (and note the @{b}&@{ub}).  This tip does @{i}not@{ui} work with literal strings.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} NameFile old$,new$
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} Rename_ &old$,&new$
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 NPRINT (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If your executable is for @{i}CLI usage only@{ui}, then use @{b}PutStr_@{ub} instead, and
 add a @{b}Chr$(10)@{ub} to the end (for the carriage-return).  This tip does @{i}not@{ui}
 work for anything other than CLI usage, so window usage and the like will
 get you nowhere.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} NPrint "Hello!"
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} PutStr_ "Hello!"+Chr$(10)
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipp "'P' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "P"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 POKE (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use @{b}MOVE@{ub} instead and swap the order of parameters.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Poke $address,#value
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} MOVE #value,$address
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 PRINT (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If your executable is for @{i}CLI usage only@{ui}, then use @{b}PutStr_@{ub} instead.  This
 tip does @{i}not@{ui} work for anything other than CLI usage, so window usage and
 the like will get you nowhere.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Print "Hello!"
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} PutStr_ "Hello!"
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipr "'R' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "R"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 REBOOT (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use @{b}ColdReboot_@{ub} instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Reboot
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} ColdReboot_
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 RENAME (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you're using @{i}variables@{ui} to specify the old/new names, then use @{b}Rename_@{ub}
 instead (and note the @{b}&@{ub}).  This tip does @{i}not@{ui} work with literal strings.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Rename old$,new$
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} Rename_ &old$,&new$
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 REPLACE$ (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Don't use @{b}Replace$@{ub} and @{b}Instr@{ub} together, because @{b}Replace$@{ub} does its own check
 of the string without needing @{b}Instr@{ub}.  If the string @{i}isn'@{ui}t found when using
 @{b}Replace$@{ub}, then the string in question is left intact; but if it @{i}is@{ui} found,
 then it gets replaced, thus doing what you wanted without using @{b}Instr@{ub}!

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} If Instr(a$,"old")<>0 Then Replace$(a$,"old","new")
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} Replace$(a$,"old","new")
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 RUN (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use @{b}Execute_@{ub} instead, but @{i}only@{ui} if you're @{i}not@{ui} using the optional @{b}stacksize@{ub}
 parameter of the command.  If you don't include the @{b}run >nil:@{ub} part, then
 your program will halt until the DOS command ends.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Run filename$,args$
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} Execute_ "run >nil: "+filename$+" "+args$,0,0
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tips "'S' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "S"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 SAVESCREEN (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 This one is a @{i}killer@{ui}, and the one responsible for motivating @{"me" link autho} to write
 this guide in the first place.  It adds a whopping @{b}8192@{ub} bytes to your final
 executable size.  That's right: this @{i}single@{ui} command stacks on another @{b}8K@{ub}!

 So what can we do?  To be honest, I don't know.  This is the only tip in
 this guide to which I don't have an optimized version for.  I've tried just
 about everything, from @{b}ScreensBitMap@{ub} and @{b}SaveBitMap@{ub} (no luck) to grabbing
 the screen as a @{b}Shape@{ub} and saving the shape (again, no luck).

 The only thing I can suggest is to @{b}IncBin@{ub} a tiny third-party screen grabber
 and call it from your code.  However, there's @{i}no point@{ui} in doing this if the
 external grabber's size is larger than 8K, because then @{b}SaveScreen@{ub} would
 become the better option.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} SaveScreen screen#,filename$

 @{i}NEW:@{ui} Call ?savescreen
      .savescreen:
      IncBin "external_grabber.exe"
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipv "'V' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "V"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 VPOS (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 Use @{b}VBeamPos_@{ub} instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} pos=VPos
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} pos=VBeamPos_
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node tipw "'W' TIPS"
@{fg shine}
>>> TIPS FOR COMMANDS STARTING WITH "W"

 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 WAITEVENT (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you're waiting for a @{i}single@{ui} IDCMP event with a window, then don't use
 the @{b}WaitEvent@{ub} and related testing commands; use @{b}WaitFor@{ub} instead.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Repeat : Until WaitEvent=$200
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} WaitFor $200
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 WBHEIGHT (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 @{b}WBHeight@{ub} has a severe bug, in that the maximum value it returns is 512.
 Thus, Workbench screens higher than 512 pixels will give a false result.
 To fix this, use the @{b}ScreenHeight@{ub} command instead (assuming you've already
 made Workbench the current screen).

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} height=WBHeight
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} height=ScreenHeight
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 WBSTARTUP (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 This should go without saying, but... If your program is for @{i}CLI usage
 only@{ui}, then @{i}don't@{ui} have @{b}WBStartup@{ub} in your code.  @{b}WBStartup@{ub} is only needed
 if you want your program to be run from a Workbench icon.
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 WBTOSCREEN (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you want to use Workbench as your screen, don't assign it to a number
 and then bring that screen to the front.  Instead, bring Workbench to the
 front first (with @{b}WBenchToFront_@{ub}) and then @{b}FindScreen@{ub} it.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} WbToScreen # : ShowScreen #
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} WBenchToFront_ : FindScreen #
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 WBWIDTH (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 @{b}WBWidth@{ub} has a severe bug, in that the maximum value it returns is 640.
 Thus, Workbench screens wider than 640 pixels will give a false result.
 To fix this, use the @{b}ScreenWidth@{ub} command instead (assuming you've already
 made Workbench the current screen).

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} width=WBWidth
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} width=ScreenWidth
@{fg shine}
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

 WINDOWOUTPUT (Paul Bowlay, cat@aic.net.au)@{fg text}

 If you're using @{b}WindowOutput@{ub} after @{b}Use Window@{ub}, then you're wasting bytes
 because @{b}Use Window@{ub} automatically does a @{b}WindowOutput@{ub} by itself.

 @{i}OLD:@{ui} Use Window # : WindowOutput #
 @{i}NEW:@{ui} Use Window #
@{fg shine}
